In this lab, we explored the Linux diff command in a software development context. We learned how to:

Compare two text files and interpret the basic diff output
Compare different versions of Python scripts
Use the unified format for more readable output
Ignore whitespace changes in comparisons
Compare entire directories recursively
Additional diff options not covered in this lab include:

-b: Ignore changes in the amount of whitespace
-u (Unified Format): Generates a readable output that shows context around the changes. This is the standard format used by version control systems like git.
-r (Recursive): Compares directories and their subdirectories recursively.
-w (Ignore Whitespace): Ignores all white space when comparing lines.
-B (Ignore Blank Lines): Ignores changes that result in inserting or deleting blank lines.
-i (Ignore Case): Ignores differences in case (treats uppercase and lowercase as the same).
-y (Side-by-Side): Displays the output in two columns, which is very helpful for visual comparisons.
-q (Brief): Only reports whether the files differ, without showing the specific changes.
--color=auto: Differentiates the output with colors, making it much easier to read (as you've already seen in your terminal!).
